<TITLE> HC extends stays on two Hasina cases </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 27 (bdnews24.com) The High Court Monday further extended the stay on proceedings against former prime minister Sheikh Hasina in the Niko and barge mounted power plant corruption cases. Justices Sheikh Rezwan Ali and Md Raisuddin made the ruling following an appeal from lawyers of the former PM, which cited the show cause notices on the Anticorruption Commission earlier handed down by the HC. On July 7, the HC stayed proceedings in both cases for two months. The court also asked the ACC to explain why proceedings in the two cases against Hasina should not be declared illegal. On Sept 27, the HC extended the stay order on the two cases to Oct 14. They were subsequently extended for a further two weeks on Oct 16. The ACC filed the Niko corruption case with Tejgaon Police Station on December 9 last year against seven individuals, including Hasina According to the case details, the accused caused a loss of Tk 13,630 crore to the state by awarding the Chhatak, Kamta and Feni gas fields to Canadian firm Niko Resources Ltd without tender. Later, the ACC submitted chargesheets against nine persons, including the former prime minister. In September last year, the ACC filed a case against seven individuals, including Hasina, accusing them of illegally awarding a contract to set up three barge mounted power plants in the private sector. It is alleged the seven received Tk 3 crore in bribes in the name of the Bangabandhu Memorial Trust in exchange for awarding the contract. Hasina was released on parole on June 11, to seek medical treatment abroad. bdnew
